[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This AI is what Photoshop should have been,&nbsp;&nbsp; and it’s a bit like reaching into a photograph&nbsp; to add the sun to it. Brighten it up a little. But this is just an illustration, so at first I&nbsp; thought this work seriously cannot be real. You&nbsp;&nbsp; see, if you have a photo and you wish to brighten&nbsp; it, no problem. Just take Photoshop. Grab one of&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'those sliders, and there we go. But, if you want&nbsp; to turn a lamp on or off, you are out of luck.&nbsp;&nbsp; Not possible. Until today. Now hold on to your&nbsp; papers Fellow Scholars, and check this out.'

[00:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'With this new AI technique, you take&nbsp; a photo, and if you wish to have&nbsp;&nbsp; the lamps on or off, you just use this&nbsp; slider. And this is where it gets wild:&nbsp;&nbsp; the system doesn’t just brighten or darken things&nbsp; - it handles reflections and shadows correctly,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'even the specular highlights on glass and&nbsp; metals. You can turn off sunlight from a window,&nbsp;&nbsp; switch on a lamp, change its color, and the&nbsp; shadows follow the physics beautifully. It’s&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[00:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like Photoshop, but actually obeying the&nbsp; laws of light transport. Absolute insanity. Turn off the lights so the cat&nbsp; can sleep better? No problem.&nbsp;&nbsp; Pretend that you’ve been studying the&nbsp; papers all day and night? No problem.'

[01:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So that was the initial shock, but&nbsp; wait, it gets even better. Now get this,&nbsp;&nbsp; it only takes 5 seconds per image. Here&nbsp; it is shown like this for our pleasure,&nbsp;&nbsp; but remember, 5 seconds. You know, the&nbsp; 5 second rule holds for this one too.'

[01:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But it goes further than that. It can even do&nbsp; things beyond all this craziness! Dear Fellow&nbsp;&nbsp; Scholars, this is Two Minute Papers with Dr.&nbsp; Károly Zsolnai-Fehér. Dr. Carroll. Get this:&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the system can even push intensity&nbsp; beyond its trained range and still&nbsp;&nbsp; produce reasonable results, including these&nbsp; neat edits. It’s like over-cranking a dimmer&nbsp;&nbsp; past 100% and it still keeps up. And it&nbsp; even works on stylized or out-of-domain&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'images - for example turning on a cartoon&nbsp; desk lamp realistically. Absolutely amazing. Also, you can add an invisible point light and&nbsp; the scene still shows plausible falloff and&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'highlights. It’s like placing a ghost flashlight&nbsp; in mid-air and the room reacts correctly. This is an AI-based technique, so how&nbsp; was it trained? How is all this possible?'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Well, first, you can take a bunch of&nbsp; rendered photos from 3D modeling systems,&nbsp;&nbsp; in this case, 20 curated scenes from&nbsp; Blender. Here, you can turn on and off&nbsp;&nbsp; lights in your rendered synthetic images as&nbsp; you like, this is a virtual world after all.'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But here is the catch, they also do real-life&nbsp; photos with lights on and off. Why is that? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp; they isolate one lamp’s effect by simple&nbsp; light arithmetic - take the ON image,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'subtract the OFF image, and you get&nbsp; exactly that lamp’s contribution.&nbsp;&nbsp; It’s like removing the band from&nbsp; a song to hear only the singer. This is the secret sauce and it is surprisingly&nbsp; elegant. We know that diffusion models can get&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'confused by unrealistic computer graphics. But&nbsp; they also need a massive amount of data to learn&nbsp;&nbsp; physics, which is hard to get from real photos.&nbsp; And the researchers found the perfect balance.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'They used a small set of of real photograph&nbsp; pairs to teach the model what real-world cameras,&nbsp;&nbsp; lenses, and lighting look like. Then, they&nbsp; used a massive dataset of over half a million&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'synthetic images to drill in the complex rules&nbsp; of shadows and reflections in countless different&nbsp;&nbsp; scenarios. The real data keeps the AI grounded in&nbsp; reality, while the synthetic data gives it a PhD&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in physics. And this is the combination that&nbsp; makes these results so incredibly plausible. So, the training mixes a small real set of real&nbsp; photos, about a few hundred, with a huge synthetic&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[03:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'set of 600k rendered images. This enables it to&nbsp; learn both real camera quirks, and physics at the&nbsp;&nbsp; same time! It’s like learning from real classrooms&nbsp; and then drilling in a flight simulator.'

[04:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But that’s actually absolutely crazy.&nbsp; To understand how monumental this is,&nbsp;&nbsp; consider the old way of doing this. You would&nbsp; need to build a full 3D model of the scene from&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the single 2D image - an almost impossible&nbsp; task. You\'d have to guess the geometry,&nbsp;&nbsp; the texture of the couch, the material of the&nbsp; floor, the roughness of the metal on the lamp.&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Only then could you try to re-render it. This&nbsp; AI sidesteps that entire impossible pipeline and&nbsp;&nbsp; somehow accomplishes it even better. By training&nbsp; on a clever mix of real and synthetic data,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it doesn\'t need to recreate the 3D scene.&nbsp; It just learns the rules of light transport.&nbsp;&nbsp; It learns exactly how light reflects off&nbsp; shiny surfaces and scatters on matte ones,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[04:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all from just looking at pixels. It\'s a&nbsp; testament to how modern AI can learn the physics&nbsp;&nbsp; of our world without us having to explicitly&nbsp; program it to do so. What a time to be alive!'

[05:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But wait, all this still should not work at all!&nbsp; Here’s why. If light transport were nonlinear,&nbsp;&nbsp; like many things in physics, that would&nbsp; mean turning a lamp on would also warp&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'materials and colors unpredictably, so ON&nbsp; minus OFF would not isolate the lamp at&nbsp;&nbsp; all. But the light transport operator in&nbsp; mathematics IS linear. Thank the Papers!&nbsp;&nbsp; That means that you can add and subtract&nbsp; these lights as if they were numbers. That&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is not trivial at all, and this property had&nbsp; to be used in this paper to make all this work. And it works beautifully. The lead author wrote&nbsp; to me about it that he is a Master student behind&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[05:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this incredible work and he’d love to be on Two&nbsp; Minute Papers. Well, there we go, the honor is&nbsp;&nbsp; mine. And man, so young, with so much talent.&nbsp; Absolutely incredible. Great job Nadav! And&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[06:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'since almost nobody is talking about this work,&nbsp; I wanted to make sure that you Fellow Scholars&nbsp;&nbsp; and the world hears about it. Like, leave a&nbsp; comment and subscribe if you’d like more of this.'
